{
  "doc_id": "2071",
  "text": "HBoV is frequently detected in patients with acute respiratory tract infection [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , including in those who are having wheezing, croup, cough, rhinorrhea and fever [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . A number of epidemiological and clinical investigations have been conducted to assess HBoV-related illness; its clinical features have been reported, which resembled those of respiratory syncytial virus (RSV) and human metapneumovirus (hMPV) infections [CITATION_6] . The most frequent clinical diagnoses associated with respiratory HBoV are general upper respiratory tract infections, bronchiolitis, pneumonia, bronchitis and asthma exacerbation [CITATION_7] . Nevertheless, few data are available related to physical characteristics and clinical severity for children with HBoV-positive LRTIs [CITATION_8] .",
